title: For Sale:  4 Winchester Model 70 SuperGrades...The Nearly-Perfect Rifle Batter
postcontent:
FOR SALE: 4 WINCHESTER MODEL 70 SUPERGRADES...THE NEARLY-PERFECT RIFLE BATTERY

This is a matching set of 4 truly unique limited production Winchester Model 70 Super Grade rifles...each of which is chambered in a cartridge that is ideal for the game animals they commemorate and is so marked with engraving on the magazine floorplate. Only 100 of these sets were made. The pictures do not do these rifles justice. They are stunning.

Rifle #1 is the Varmint Rifle chambered in the blistering 22-250. Rifle #2 is the Deer/Antelope Rifle chambered in the flat shooting 270 Win. Rifle #3 is the Elk/Moose chambered in the potent 300 Win Mag. Rifle #4 is the Dangerous Game Rifle and is chambered in 375 H&H Mag. All of the classic Model 70 Super Grade features are present – the fancy grade checkered walnut stock with shadowline cheeckpiece and ebony fore-end tip, the engraved crossbolt head and the traditional Super Grade pistol grip cap. Each of these beautiful rifles is built with the Pre-’64 style action that offers a forged steel receiver, massive external claw extractor, controlled round feeding and reliable blade ejection. 

Not only did Winchester only make 100 of these 4 rifle sets but...they do not make a Model 70 SuperGrade in 22-250 or 375 H&H Mag. This adds to the value and uniqueness of this set. These rifles are NIB...never been fired. 

I spoke with an official at the Midway Foundation who informed me that these rifles are among the last Model 70 Super Grades that were manufactured in American facilities. Future manufacturing is being moved to Japan. Get the last of the American made Model 70 Super Grades while you can!

title: For Sale:  East German marked 1943 Izzy Mosin Nagant 91/30 with ammo
postcontent:
For sale is a lovely DDR marked 91/30 Mosin, with "triangle 1" stamp on receiver and "r" date suffix. These were given to the Commie regime there after WW2 and used to guard the Berlin Wall during the Cold War. They were sent to the armory in Suhl, Germany, graded, then issued. Most Mosin shooters and collectors only come by these by accident, and they are generally beautiful rifles with perfect bores, crowns, and numbers matching. This on is no exception. Only 12 rounds have been fired from it once removed from cosmoline, its accurate and hits reliably at 240 yards as of this posting. Stock is Soviet return, wood not laminate, and bluing on this rifle is exceptional.

With this purchase, I'm including 50+ rounds of soviet ball ammo and 16 rounds of 203 grains Brown Bear soft point. I've hunted with 91/30s, and while heavy, they are quite deadly. Large deer fall easily to the 203 gr. 

Pictures by email only. Text REDACTED or as stated, email. I tend to check both frequently.
Price has dropped. Will go no lower. Local pickup within 10 miles of my home, be prepared to meet FTF.

Like new with 120 rounds fired.  Originally designed for the American market, the USP (Universal Self-loading Pistol) has found international acceptance as an accurate and ultra-reliable handgun.  

All USPs use a fiber-reinforced polymer frame stiffened by stainless steel inserts at areas subject to stress and friction. The USP control lever, a combination safety and decocking lever, is frame mounted and quickly accessible, unlike the slide-mounted safeties common on many semi-automatic pistols.  Using a modified Browning-type action with a special patented recoil reduction system, the USP recoil reduction system reduces recoil effects on pistol components and also lowers the recoil forces felt by the shooter. This same recoil reduction system has been tested and proven in the HK Mark 23 pistol developed for the U.S. Special Operations Command. The USP recoil reduction system is insensitive to ammunition types and requires no special adjustment or maintenance.
